### 3. Content-aware in/out points (cheapest high-impact edit)

**Architectural fix first:** transcribe the source (or a coarse pass) before cutting. Cheap options that fit your stack:
- Run faster-whisper on the **whole source** with `vad_filter=True` (Silero VAD) and a small/distil model on CPU first to get rough segments, then a higher-quality pass only on candidate regions. Per the SYSTRAN/faster-whisper README, the library is "up to 4 times faster than openai/whisper for the same accuracy while using less memory," and "can be further improved with 8-bit quantization on both CPU and GPU."
- Or VAD-segment first (Silero via faster-whisper's `vad_parameters=dict(min_silence_duration_ms=500)`), transcribe only speech regions.
- Get word timestamps: `segments,_ = model.transcribe(path, word_timestamps=True)` → each `word.start`, `word.end`.

**Snap START to the sentence/utterance that sets up the peak; snap END to the end of a sentence or laugh.**
- **Detect utterance boundaries from word timings:** a gap `word[i+1].start - word[i].end > 0.4–0.6s` is a likely sentence/utterance boundary; also break on terminal punctuation (`. ? !`) which Whisper attaches to the word. (WhisperX/stable-ts give cleaner sentence grouping if you want it; stable-ts has `split_by_gap`/`merge_by_gap` and `clamp_max` helpers.)
- **Start point:** from the scored peak, walk backwards to the start of the utterance containing the setup (often 1–2 sentences before the payoff). This is what gives the clip a hook instead of dropping the viewer mid-thought.
- **End point:** walk forward to the end of the current sentence; if a laughter segment overlaps or immediately follows, extend to the end of the laugh so the reaction lands. Never cut mid-word — clamp the out-point to the nearest `word.end`.

This snap-to-speech logic is the same reason ClipsAI cuts on transcript segment boundaries rather than fixed durations.

